  <!-- 10. User Flows -->
  <SectionContent title="User Flows">
    <div class="cs-body-text">
      <p>We mapped five core flows that represent the full lifecycle of building and managing a workflow automation. Each one was designed to reduce cognitive load at the exact moments where users tend to hesitate, second-guess, or abandon the process entirely.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Flow 1: Creating a Workflow -->
    <div class="cs-subsection">
      <h3 class="cs-subsection-title">Flow 1: Creating a Workflow</h3>
      <div class="cs-flow-pills">
        <span><strong>Open Workflow Builder</strong> &rarr; Click "New Workflow" from the dashboard &rarr; Name the workflow in a modal dialog</span>
        <span><strong>Land on Canvas</strong> &rarr; Guided empty state appears with "Add a Trigger" prompt &rarr; Dotted drop zone shows where to start</span>
        <span><strong>Select First Trigger</strong> &rarr; Sidebar auto-opens with searchable trigger list (App Event, Webhook, Schedule, Forms) &rarr; Drag trigger onto the canvas drop zone</span>
        <span><strong>Trigger Activates</strong> &rarr; Drop zone changes color to confirm placement &rarr; Sidebar switches to trigger setup with Setup/Conditions/Test tabs &rarr; Floating "+" button appears for adding next steps</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-body-text" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <p>The biggest risk here was the blank canvas. Early versions dropped users onto an empty screen with no guidance. We solved this with a guided empty state that tells users exactly what to do first, eliminating the "where do I even start?" moment.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-image-full" style="margin-top: 32px;" set:html={flow1} />
    </div>

    <!-- Flow 2: Configuring Triggers & Actions -->
    <div class="cs-subsection" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <h3 class="cs-subsection-title">Flow 2: Configuring Triggers & Actions</h3>
      <div class="cs-flow-pills">
        <span><strong>Configure Trigger</strong> &rarr; Select event type from dropdown &rarr; Connect account via inline OAuth flow &rarr; Required fields marked with clear indicators</span>
        <span><strong>Add Action Steps</strong> &rarr; Click "+" button or drag from sidebar panel &rarr; Choose action type (Send Email, Save Data, API Call) &rarr; Each step auto-opens its setup sidebar</span>
        <span><strong>Map Fields</strong> &rarr; Map data from trigger to action fields &rarr; Dynamic field suggestions based on connected apps &rarr; Live preview of mapped values</span>
        <span><strong>Build the Sequence</strong> &rarr; Add multiple actions in sequence &rarr; Reorder via drag and drop &rarr; Live auto-save indicator confirms progress is preserved</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-body-text" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <p>Users needed to feel like they were making progress, not just filling out forms. The sidebar stays contextual to whatever node is selected, and the auto-save indicator removes the anxiety of losing work mid-setup.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-image-full" style="margin-top: 32px;" set:html={flow2} />
    </div>

    <!-- Flow 3: Configuring Split Paths -->
    <div class="cs-subsection" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <h3 class="cs-subsection-title">Flow 3: Configuring Split Paths (Branching Logic)</h3>
      <div class="cs-flow-pills">
        <span><strong>Add Split Path Node</strong> &rarr; Choose between Conditional Split or Percentage Split &rarr; Clear descriptions explain when to use each type</span>
        <span><strong>Define Conditions</strong> &rarr; Build rules with AND/OR logic builder &rarr; Inline condition summaries appear on canvas paths &rarr; Readable at a glance without opening the sidebar</span>
        <span><strong>Add Steps to Branches</strong> &rarr; Each branch gets its own "+" button for adding actions &rarr; Merge paths toggle controls whether branches rejoin downstream</span>
        <span><strong>Validate Paths</strong> &rarr; Confirmation dialog before deleting paths with existing steps &rarr; Visual preview shows which contacts route down which path &rarr; Edit any branch without restarting from the beginning</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-body-text" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <p>Branching logic is where most workflow tools lose people. We made the split type decision easy with plain-language descriptions, kept conditions readable on the canvas itself, and added safeguards against accidental deletion of configured paths.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-image-full" style="margin-top: 32px;" set:html={flow3} />
    </div>

    <!-- Flow 4: Testing a Workflow -->
    <div class="cs-subsection" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <h3 class="cs-subsection-title">Flow 4: Testing a Workflow</h3>
      <div class="cs-flow-pills">
        <span><strong>Initiate Test</strong> &rarr; Click "Run Test" from the toolbar or right-click context menu &rarr; Choose test scope: single step, single trigger, or entire workflow</span>
        <span><strong>Review Results</strong> &rarr; Pass/fail indicator per connection &rarr; Green checkmarks for successful steps, red error borders for failed nodes &rarr; Expandable details show exactly what went wrong</span>
        <span><strong>Debug &amp; Fix</strong> &rarr; Click failed node to jump directly to its configuration &rarr; Fix the issue in the sidebar without leaving the test view &rarr; Error context preserved so users know what to change</span>
        <span><strong>Re-test</strong> &rarr; "Test Again" button for iterative debugging &rarr; Results update in real-time &rarr; All steps must pass before the publish button becomes available</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-body-text" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <p>Testing was the biggest trust-builder in the entire flow. Users told us they would never publish something they couldn't verify first. The inline debugging loop (test, see error, fix, re-test) kept them in flow state instead of bouncing between screens.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-image-full" style="margin-top: 32px;" set:html={flow4} />
    </div>

    <!-- Flow 5: Publishing & Managing Workflows -->
    <div class="cs-subsection" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <h3 class="cs-subsection-title">Flow 5: Publishing & Managing Workflows</h3>
      <div class="cs-flow-pills">
        <span><strong>Publish</strong> &rarr; Two-step confirmation dialog: "This workflow will go live" in plain language &rarr; Blue "Yes, publish" button with cancel option &rarr; No ambiguity about what happens next</span>
        <span><strong>Success State</strong> &rarr; "Congratulations, your workflow is now live!" celebration screen &rarr; "Go To Dashboard" or "Keep Working" options &rarr; Clear next steps instead of a dead end</span>
        <span><strong>Manage from Dashboard</strong> &rarr; Track all workflows with status badges (Live, Draft, Paused) &rarr; Search, filter, and sort by name, status, or date &rarr; Context menus for rename, duplicate, pause, unpublish, and delete</span>
        <span><strong>Lifecycle Actions</strong> &rarr; Pause or unpublish live workflows with confirmation &rarr; Version history with rollback to previous states &rarr; 30-day trash recovery for deleted workflows &rarr; Exit confirmation prevents accidental abandonment</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-body-text" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <p>Publishing should feel like a milestone, not a gamble. The two-step confirmation removes doubt, the success state provides emotional closure, and the dashboard gives users long-term control over everything they've built.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-image-full" style="margin-top: 32px;" set:html={flow5} />
    </div>

    <p style={flowLabel}>Legend</p>
    <div class="cs-image-full" style="max-width: 380px; margin-left: 0; margin-right: auto; margin-top: 0;" set:html={flowLegend} />

    <blockquote class="cs-pullquote" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <svg class="cs-pullquote-icon" width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 21c3 0 7-1 7-8V5c0-1.25-.756-2.017-2-2H4c-1.25 0-2 .75-2 1.972V11c0 1.25.75 2 2 2 1 0 1 0 1 1v1c0 1-1 2-2 2s-1 .008-1 1.031V21z"/><path d="M15 21c3 0 7-1 7-8V5c0-1.25-.757-2.017-2-2h-4c-1.25 0-2 .75-2 1.972V11c0 1.25.75 2 2 2 1 0 1 0 1 1v1c0 1-1 2-2 2s-1 .008-1 1.031V21z"/></svg>
      The hardest part wasn't building the features.<br>It was making complex logic feel effortless.
    </blockquote>
  </SectionContent>

